SIMPLE: saturation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Saturation
<hw>Sat`u*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>saturatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>saturation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of saturating, or the state of being saturating; complete
penetration or impregnation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>The act, process, or result of
saturating a substance, or of combining it to its fullest
extent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Optics)</fld> <def>Freedom from mixture or dilution
with white; purity; -- said of colors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The degree of <xex>saturation</xex> of a color is its
relative purity, or freedom from admixture with white.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Saturator</ent>⟦br⟧
